<tt>Thu Jan 16 16:09:17 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To RN Dusty and all the other RVN Nurses,<br>
I was wounded twice working as a medic in the 1st Cav., and was lucky enough to have been able to treat myself in the field (flash burns, minor shrapnel).<br><br>
The last month of my stay in Nam, I contracted malaria, and was told later that I had been infected by the vivax and falciparum strains simutaneously.(possible?) I delayed leaving the field for as long as I could, until I became ineffective.  I was medivaced to a hospital, (location and name unknown) where,(perceived at that time) I suffered the degration and humiliation of being stripped of my aidbag, poncho liner, and my weapon (all of my survivor tools).  I had a 107 degree temp (cooked more than one brain cell).  I was then restrained in a bed, had ice packs placed behind my neck, in my arm pits, in my crotch, and under my knees.  I then had a cooling (ice) blanket draped on me.  Veins in my extremities had collapse.  Numerous attempts (painful)to start an I.V. from my scalp to my feet proved unsuccessful and they had to do a cutdown.  Most times, for the next three or four days, I was not in my right mind.  During my few lucid times, absence the dreams, nightmares and hallucinations, I was rude and abusive to the RN's around me. When I could talk(yell) in between the dry heaving from the quinine, I called them everything I could think of, threatened them with all I could think of.  Needless to say, when the fever finally broke, the RN's, understandably, were not hospitable to me.  As I remember, I stayed in the hospital for a total of two weeks before being allowed to go back to my platoon.<br><br>
Before God and all those reading this, I apologize for my conduct.  I thank you all for saving my life.  I also thank you from the bottom of my heart for your care of the men from my unit.<br><br>
I have a ten year old daughter.  Should she chose to be an R.N. in the military, and have to serve during wartime, I would be most proud.  The only difference would be that I would not treat her as our families and friends treated us after coming home.
